 "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals with photochemical assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed cyanosulfidic setting, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is specifically identified in the supplied literature as a key prebiotic intermediate formed from formaldehyde and HCN in cyanosulfidic chemistry; surface UV and sulfide-rich settings are appropriate for this chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface homologation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or geothermal field; formose-type carbon-carbon bond formation"}, "mechanism": "Formose-like carbon-carbon coupling produces the C2 aldehyde, with borate stabilizing sugar-like products.", "reasoning": "The literature summary highlights formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and sugar-forming chemistry as important precursor pools. Borate-stabilized formose chemistry is a standard prebiotic route to glycolaldehyde and provides the required aldehyde for serine Strecker chemistry (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface hydrolysis/oxidation of glycolonitrile to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted hydrolysis and oxidation under anoxic surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis followed by oxidation/rearrangement furnishes glyoxylate from glycolonitrile-derived pools.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies glyoxylate as a major intermediate connected to formaldehyde/glycine chemistry and glycolonitrile as a key cyanosulfidic precursor. The exact environmental conversion sequence is not fully resolved, so this step is a literature-guided connector between those experimentally recognized pools (Springsteen & Joyce, 2004; Ritson et al., 2018; speculative integration noted)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent to subseafloor gradient, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation builds a C3 alpha-keto acid from CO2/H2 equivalents.", "reasoning": "The supplied research explicitly identifies pyruvate as an important prebiotic intermediate, especially in Fe2+-catalyzed or hydrothermal settings, and the system instructions require hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite as a central route (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrothermal/surface production of HCN pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 with sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven atmosphere-surface interface; network feedstock node"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical redox processing of reduced C/N feedstocks contributes to cyanide inventory available to surface pools.", "reasoning": "The literature provided treats HCN as a core prebiotic feedstock for serine synthesis and surface UV chemistry as a plausible source domain, though serine-specific HCN sourcing is not resolved in the report. This reaction is therefore included as a necessary network feed into experimentally supported downstream Strecker chemistry and is explicitly marked as a generalized prebiotic HCN-source step (Miller, 1957; Ranjan & Sasselov, 2017; speculative integration from supplied review)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite-assisted concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or aqueous surface setting, neutral to mildly basic"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imination with ammonia followed by cyanide addition forms the alpha-aminonitrile corresponding to serine.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest literature-supported route in the supplied report: aldehydes such as HOCH2CHO react with NH3 and HCN to form alpha-aminonitriles that hydrolyze to serine. Glycolaldehyde is the correct C2 hydroxyaldehyde precursor for serine Strecker chemistry (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984; review support in Cleaves, 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker conversion of glycolaldehyde to N-phosphoro-serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate with phosphate mineral buffering", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH, selective phosphoro-Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "DAP activates the aldehyde/amine/cyanide sequence to yield an N-phosphoroaminonitrile selectively.", "reasoning": "The research report explicitly identifies phosphoro-Strecker synthesis using DAP, aldehydes, and HCN at neutral pH as a selective prebiotic amino-acid route applicable to serine. This reaction directly follows that literature guidance (Krishnamurthy et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of serine nitrile to serine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool hydrolysis over time; neutral to mildly acidic/basic cycling"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the amino acid serine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to alpha-amino acids is canonical and is specifically cited in the supplied serine literature as the completion step from the alpha-aminonitrile to serine (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Bada, 1991)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis/dephosphorylation of N-phosphoro-serine nitrile to serine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "basic to neutral aqueous workup in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "The N-phosphoroaminonitrile undergoes hydrolysis and loss of phosphate to give the amino acid product.", "reasoning": "The phosphoro-Strecker literature cited in the supplied report specifically describes N-phosphoroaminonitriles as amino-acid precursors that can be converted to amino acids under aqueous conditions; this is the selective serine-forming branch (Krishnamurthy et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Non-enzymatic transamination/reductive amination of hydroxypyruvate to serine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-303K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "25-30 C, mil