ollowed by hydrolytic turnover replenishes hydroxyaldehyde feedstock pools.", "reasoning": "The report links glycolonitrile, phosphate chemistry, and hydroxyaldehyde feedstocks within broader cyanosulfidic networks, though this exact recycling step is not explicitly demonstrated for serine. It is included as a conservative connector to create literature-consistent network interconversion among observed precursor pools (Patel et al., 2015; Krishnamurthy et al., 2019; speculative integration stated)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "HCN oligomerization reservoir feeding cyanide chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV and mineral surface concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "tidal flat or evaporitic concentration regime"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated cyanide undergoes oligomerization into higher nitrile reservoirs that buffer and recycle cyanide chemistry.", "reasoning": "The supplied report notes HCN oligomerization to DAMN and related nucleobase precursor pools as a standard surface reaction type. While not serine-forming directly, it creates a connected cyanide reservoir consistent with early Earth chemistry and with HCN-centered networks (Ferris et al., 1978; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Cyanide reservoir turnover back to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV/mineral reprocessing", "aqueous": "true", "other": "photolabile cyanide reservoir turnover"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and hydrolytic fragmentation of HCN oligomer pools regenerates free cyanide equivalents.", "reasoning": "The serine literature stresses HCN as a key persistent feedstock despite network complexity. Including reversible reservoir